Reena’s 1 hour’s work = $ rac{1}{6}$;
Aastha’s 1 hour’s work = $ rac{1}{4}$;
Shloka’s 1 hour’s work = $ rac{1}{12}$.
(Reena + Aastha + Shloka)’s 1 hour’s work
$=  rac{1}{6} +  rac{1}{4} +  rac{1}{12} =  rac{2+3+1}{12} =  rac{6}{12} =  rac{1}{2}$.
Hence, Reena, Aastha and Shloka together take 2 hours to complete the work.

(A + B + C)'s 1 day's work = $\frac{1}{6}$;
(A + B)'s 1 day's work = $\frac{1}{8}$;
(B + C)'s 1 day's work = $\frac{1}{12}$.
(A + C)'s 1 day's work
$= \left(2 \times \frac{1}{6} - \left(\frac{1}{8} + \frac{1}{12}\right)\right) = \left(\frac{1}{3} - \frac{5}{24}\right) = \frac{3}{24} = \frac{1}{8}$.
So, A and C together will do the work in 8 days.

(A + B)'s 1 day's work = $\frac{1}{5}$;
(B + C)'s 1 day's work = $\frac{1}{7}$;
(A + C)'s 1 day's work = $\frac{1}{4}$.
Adding, we get: $2$ (A + B + C)'s 1 day's work
$= \left(\frac{1}{5} + \frac{1}{7} + \frac{1}{4}\right) = \frac{83}{140}$.
(A + B + C)'s 1 day's work = $\frac{83}{280}$.
A's 1 day's work = $\left(\frac{83}{280} - \frac{1}{7}\right) = \frac{43}{280}$;
B's 1 day's work = $\left(\frac{83}{280} - \frac{1}{4}\right) = \frac{13}{280}$;
C's 1 day's work = $\left(\frac{83}{280} - \frac{1}{5}\right) = \frac{27}{280}$.
Thus time taken by A, B, C is $\frac{280}{43}$ days, $\frac{280}{13}$ days, $\frac{280}{27}$ days respectively.
Clearly, the time taken by A is least.

Boy’s 1 day’s work = $ rac{1}{3} -  rac{1}{7} -  rac{1}{8} =  rac{56-24-21}{168} =  rac{11}{168}$.
Ratio of wages of the first man, second man and boy
= $ rac{1}{7} :  rac{1}{8} :  rac{11}{168} = 24 : 21 : 11$.
First man’s share = ₹ $ rac{24}{56} 	imes 1400$ = ₹ 600;
Second man’s share = ₹ $ rac{21}{56} 	imes 1400$ = ₹ 525;
Boy’s share = ₹ $[1400 - (600 + 525)]$ = ₹ 275.

(A + B)’s 6 days’ work = $ rac{6}{20} =  rac{3}{10}$;
(A + C)’s 4 days’ work = $1 -  rac{3}{10} =  rac{7}{10}$;
(A + C)’s 1 day’s work = $ rac{7}{40}$. A’s 1 day’s work = $ rac{1}{20}$.
∴ C’s 1 day’s work = $ rac{7}{40} -  rac{1}{20} =  rac{1}{40}$.
Hence, C alone can finish the work in 40 days.
